{"title_page": "Kurt vid Stein", "text_new": "{{short description|Danish cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Kurt vid Stein\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| fullname      = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1935|11|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = \n| role          = \n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = \n}}\n\n'''Kurt vid Stein''' (born 17 November 1935) is a former Danish [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed at the [[1960 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1964 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/vi/kurt-vid-stein-1.html |title=Kurt vid Stein Olympic Results |accessdate=9 August 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vid Stein, Kurt}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1964 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Copenhagen]]\n{{Denmark-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Kurt vid Stein\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| fullname      = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1935|11|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = \n| role          = \n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = \n}}\n\n'''Kurt vid Stein''' (born 17 November 1935) is a former Danish [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed at the [[1960 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1964 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/vi/kurt-vid-stein-1.html |title=Kurt vid Stein Olympic Results |accessdate=9 August 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vid Stein, Kurt}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1964 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Copenhagen]]\n{{Denmark-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kurt_vid_Stein"}
{"title_page": "Cartoon Art Museum", "text_new": "{{confused|The Cartoon Museum|National Cartoon Museum}}\n{{Infobox museum\n| name = Cartoon Art Museum\n| logo = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| alt = \n| map_type = San Francisco County#California#USA\n| map_caption = \n| former_name = \n| established = 1984\n| location = 781 Beach Street, San Francisco, California\n| coordinates = {{coord|37.8062666|-122.4238831|display=inline}}\n| type = The art of [[comics]] and [[cartoons]]\n| collection = 6,000 pieces\n| visitors = \n| director = Summerlea Kashar\n| president = \n| curator = [[Andrew Farago]]\n| website = {{url|www.cartoonart.org}}\n| network = \n| map_alt = |\n}}\nThe '''Cartoon Art Museum''' ('''CAM''') is a California art museum that specializes in the art of [[comics]] and [[cartoons]]. It is the only museum in the [[Western United States]] dedicated to the preservation and exhibition of all forms of cartoon art.<ref>[http://arts.stanford.edu/event/curating-cartoons-andrew-farago-cartoon-art-museum/ \"Curating Cartoons (Andrew Farago, Cartoon Art Museum),\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202093104/http://arts.stanford.edu/event/curating-cartoons-andrew-farago-cartoon-art-museum/ |date=February 2, 2014 }} ''Stanford Arts'' (Jan. 9, 2014).</ref> The permanent collection features some 7,000 pieces as of 2015, including original [[animation]] [[cel]]s, [[comic book]] pages and sculptures.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Cartoon Art Museum to vacate longtime SoMa home|url = http://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Cartoon-Art-Museum-to-vacate-longtime-SoMa-home-6208311.php|accessdate = 2015-04-18|publisher = San Francisco Chronicle|last = Vaziri|first = Aidin|date = April 18, 2015|quote = The institution [...] has to vacate its home in San Francisco's South of Market neighborhood after its longtime lease ends in June, but has not yet found a new one. [... It ] counts approximately 7,000 original pieces as part of its permanent collection, including comic strips, political cartoons, comic book pages, advertisements, sculptures, videos and animation cels, backgrounds and sketches.}}</ref>\n\nUntil September 2015, the museum was located in the [[Yerba Buena Gardens]] cultural district of [[San Francisco]], in the [[South of Market]] neighborhood. It reopened in October 2017, in a new location in the [[Fisherman's Wharf, San Francisco, California|Fisherman's Wharf]] area of [[San Francisco]].\n\n== History ==\nThe Museum was founded in 1984 by comic art enthusiasts,<ref>Tanner, Marcia. \"Getting Serious About the Comics,\" ''San Francisco Chronicle'' (03 Feb 1993), p. 7/Z1.</ref> with its primary founder being [[Malcolm Whyte]], the publisher of [[Troubador Press]]. CAM's first incarnation had no fixed location, instead organizing showings at other local museums and corporate spaces. In 1987, with the help of an endowment from cartoonist [[Charles Schulz]], it established a home on the second floor of the [[San Francisco Call|San Francisco Call-Bulletin]] Building in the [[South of Market (San Francisco)|South of Market]] (SoMa) area.\n\nIn late 1994 the museum temporarily closed while it moved locations again;<ref>\"Newswatch: Cartoon Art Museum also on the Move,\" ''The Comics Journal'' #173 (Dec. 1994), p. 38.</ref> re-opening in the summer of 1995.<ref>Stephenson, Chad. \"Newswatch: The Cartoon Art Museum: A Grand Re-Opening,\" ''The Comics Journal'' #178 (July 1995), pp. 26-28.</ref> Primary founder Malcolm Whyte retired from the museum's board of directors around the same time.<ref>\"Founder of Cartoon Art Museum Retires,\" ''The Comics Journal'' #179 (Aug. 1995), p. 25.</ref>\n\nIn 1997, the museum suffered through serious financial difficulties, and was almost forced to close<ref>Stump, Greg.\"Newswatch: Comics Museums Facing Financial Crisis,\" ''The Comics Journal'' #198 (Aug. 1997), pp. 11-15.</ref>\u2014this was despite a new endowment fund from the [[Charles M. Schulz|Schulz Foundation]].<ref>\"News Watch: Schulz Foundation Sets Up Endowment Fund for Cartoon Art Museum,\" ''The Comics Journal'' #195 (Apr. 1997), p. 24.</ref> \n\nJenny E. Robb served as curator of the Cartoon Art Museum from 2000\u20132005. (Robb is now curator of the [[Billy Ireland Cartoon Library & Museum]] in Columbus, Ohio.) Current curator [[Andrew Farago]] took over from Robb in 2005.\n\nIn 2001, the museum moved to a ground-floor location at 655 Mission Street in SoMa, which had been vacated by the [[Ansel Adams|Friends of Photography Ansel Adams Center]]{{Cn|date = April 2015}}. It closed the location in mid-September 2015 after the lease expired; the owners more than doubled the rent.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn late 2016, the museum signed a 10-year lease on a historic, 8,000-square-foot brick building a block away from [[Ghirardelli Square|Ghiradelli Square]]. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/11/03/cartoon-art-museum-finds-new-home-in-san-francisco/|title=Cartoon Art Museum Finds New Home in San Francisco|work=KQED Arts|access-date=2017-11-08|language=en-us}}</ref> Almost a year later, during late October 2017, the Cartoon Art Museum finally reopened its doors at its new location with three new exhibitions, including a retrospective of the San Francisco cartoonist [[Raina Telgemeier]], a tribute exhibition of [[Mike Mignola]]'s [[Hellboy]], and the emerging artist showcase featuring [[Nidhi Chanani]].\n\n== Sparky Award ==\nOver the years, the Museum has presented the '''Sparky Award''' (after the nickname of [[Charles M. Schulz]]), in honor of the lifetime achievement of prominent creators in the fields of cartooning and animation who \"embody the talent, innovation and humanity of Schulz.\"<ref name=Colan /> The award, which is co-sponsored by the [[Charles M. Schulz Museum]], includes a statuette of [[Snoopy]] holding a pen and leaning on an [[inkwell]]. (The CAM Sparky Award is not connected to the award of the same name presented at the [[Slamdance Film Festival]].)\n\nThe award debuted in 1998,<ref name=Flessel /> and multiple winners were announced each year until 2001. After a six-year hiatus, the award was again presented in 2007. The most recent Sparky Award was given in 2015.<ref name=Turner />\n\nThe Sparky Award has been presented at various venues, including the [[San Diego Comic-Con]] and the [[New York Comic Con]].\n\n'''List of Sparky Award winners''':<ref>[http://cartoonart.org/events/sparky-awards 2001 Sparky Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112005358/http://cartoonart.org/events/sparky-awards/ |date=2014-01-12 }}, www.cartoonart.org. Accessed Jan. 28, 2014.</ref>\n* 1998&nbsp;\u2013 [[Charles M. Schulz]], [[Chuck Jones]], and [[John Lasseter]]\n* 1999&nbsp;\u2013 [[Sergio Aragon\u00e9s]], [[Gus Arriola]], [[Carl Barks]], and [[Dale Messick]]\n* 2000&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ward Kimball]], [[Stan Lee]], and [[Morrie Turner]]\n* 2001&nbsp;\u2013 [[John Severin]], [[Will Eisner]], [[Phil Frank]], [[Lou Grant (cartoonist)|Lou Grant]], [[Gary Larson]], and [[Bill Mel\u00e9ndez]]\n* 2007&nbsp;\u2013 [[Creig Flessel]]<ref name=Flessel>Klien, Gary.\n[http://www.marinij.com/ci_7309002 \"Marin cartoonist, 95, wins 'Sparky' award,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222024248/http://www.marinij.com/ci_7309002 |date=2014-02-22 }} ''Marin Independent Journal'' (Oct. 28, 2007).</ref>\n* 2008&nbsp;\u2013 [[Gene Colan]]<ref name=Colan>[http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=19141 \"Gene Colan Awarded Sparky Award,\"] ''Comic Book Resources'' (December 11th, 2008).</ref> (and, in an earlier ceremony, [[Malcolm Whyte]])<ref>Garchik, Leah. [http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Friends-recall-William-Buckley-s-grace-3226277.php \"Friends recall William Buckley's grace,\"] ''San Francisco Chronicle'' (February 29, 2008): \"The Cartoon Art Museum in San Francisco threw a surprise 75th birthday party last week for its founder, Malcolm Whyte. The museum, which Whyte founded 25 years ago, is the world's largest devoted to cartoon art. Jeannie Schulz presented a Cartoon Art Museum \"Sparky\" award, named after her late husband, Charles Schulz, to Whyte, who was also given a caricature of himself by artist Zach Trenholm.\"</ref>\n* 2010&nbsp;\u2013 [[Mort Walker]]\n* 2011&nbsp;\u2013 [[Jerry Robinson]]\n* 2015&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ron Turner (publisher)|Ron Turner]]\u2014presented in conjunction with the first annual [[San Francisco Comics Fest]]<ref name=Turner>[http://icv2.com/articles/news/view/31529/san-francisco-proclaims-may-5-ron-turner-day \"SAN FRANCISCO PROCLAIMS MAY 5 'RON TURNER DAY': Legendary Publisher Also Gets 'Sparky Award',\"] ''ICv2'' (May 7, 2015).\n* 2017&nbsp;\u2013 [[Jeff Smith (cartoonist)|Jeff Smith]] presented at the Charles M. Schulz Museum and Research Center</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\nThe Museum hosts nine to 12 major exhibitions annually, along with classes for children and adults. It also offers lectures and operates a research library, a classroom and a bookstore.\n\n{{Portal|San Francisco Bay Area}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://cartoonart.org/}}\n* [https://twitter.com/cartoonart/ Twitter page]\n\n{{Comics}}\n{{Bay Area Arts Organizations}}\n{{San Francisco Attractions}}\n\n{{Coord|37.787088|-122.400940|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Art museums in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Cartooning museums]]\n[[Category:Media museums in California]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1984]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:South of Market, San Francisco]]\n[[Category:1984 in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Charles M. Schulz]]\n", "text_old": "{{confused|The Cartoon Museum|National Cartoon Museum}}\n{{Infobox museum\n| name = Cartoon Art Museum\n| logo = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| alt = \n| map_type = San Francisco County#California#USA\n| map_caption = \n| former_name = \n| established = 1984\n| location = 781 Beach Street, San Francisco, California\n| coordinates = {{coord|37.8062666|-122.4238831|display=inline}}\n| type = The art of [[comics]] and [[cartoons]]\n| collection = 6,000 pieces\n| visitors = \n| director = Summerlea Kashar\n| president = \n| curator = [[Andrew Farago]]\n| website = {{url|www.cartoonart.org}}\n| network = \n| map_alt = |\n}}\nThe '''Cartoon Art Museum''' ('''CAM''') is a California art museum that specializes in the art of [[comics]] and [[cartoons]]. It is the only museum in the [[Western United States]] dedicated to the preservation and exhibition of all forms of cartoon art.<ref>[http://arts.stanford.edu/event/curating-cartoons-andrew-farago-cartoon-art-museum/ \"Curating Cartoons (Andrew Farago, Cartoon Art Museum),\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202093104/http://arts.stanford.edu/event/curating-cartoons-andrew-farago-cartoon-art-museum/ |date=February 2, 2014 }} ''Stanford Arts'' (Jan. 9, 2014).</ref> The permanent collection features some 7,000 pieces as of 2015, including original [[animation]] [[cel]]s, [[comic book]] pages and sculptures.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Cartoon Art Museum to vacate longtime SoMa home|url = http://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Cartoon-Art-Museum-to-vacate-longtime-SoMa-home-6208311.php|accessdate = 2015-04-18|publisher = San Francisco Chronicle|last = Vaziri|first = Aidin|date = April 18, 2015|quote = The institution [...] has to vacate its home in San Francisco's South of Market neighborhood after its longtime lease ends in June, but has not yet found a new one. [... It ] counts approximately 7,000 original pieces as part of its permanent collection, including comic strips, political cartoons, comic book pages, advertisements, sculptures, videos and animation cels, backgrounds and sketches.}}</ref>\n\nUntil September 2015, the museum was located in the [[Yerba Buena Gardens]] cultural district of [[San Francisco]], in the [[South of Market]] neighborhood. It reopened October 2017, in a new location in the [[Fisherman's Wharf, San Francisco, California|Fisherman's Wharf]] area of [[San Francisco]].\n\n== History ==\nThe Museum was founded in 1984 by comic art enthusiasts,<ref>Tanner, Marcia. \"Getting Serious About the Comics,\" ''San Francisco Chronicle'' (03 Feb 1993), p. 7/Z1.</ref> with its primary founder being [[Malcolm Whyte]], the publisher of [[Troubador Press]]. CAM's first incarnation had no fixed location, instead organizing showings at other local museums and corporate spaces. In 1987, with the help of an endowment from cartoonist [[Charles Schulz]], it established a home on the second floor of the [[San Francisco Call|San Francisco Call-Bulletin]] Building in the [[South of Market (San Francisco)|South of Market]] (SoMa) area.\n\nIn late 1994 the museum temporarily closed while it moved locations again;<ref>\"Newswatch: Cartoon Art Museum also on the Move,\" ''The Comics Journal'' #173 (Dec. 1994), p. 38.</ref> re-opening in the summer of 1995.<ref>Stephenson, Chad. \"Newswatch: The Cartoon Art Museum: A Grand Re-Opening,\" ''The Comics Journal'' #178 (July 1995), pp. 26-28.</ref> Primary founder Malcolm Whyte retired from the museum's board of directors around the same time.<ref>\"Founder of Cartoon Art Museum Retires,\" ''The Comics Journal'' #179 (Aug. 1995), p. 25.</ref>\n\nIn 1997, the museum suffered through serious financial difficulties, and was almost forced to close<ref>Stump, Greg.\"Newswatch: Comics Museums Facing Financial Crisis,\" ''The Comics Journal'' #198 (Aug. 1997), pp. 11-15.</ref>\u2014this was despite a new endowment fund from the [[Charles M. Schulz|Schulz Foundation]].<ref>\"News Watch: Schulz Foundation Sets Up Endowment Fund for Cartoon Art Museum,\" ''The Comics Journal'' #195 (Apr. 1997), p. 24.</ref> \n\nJenny E. Robb served as curator of the Cartoon Art Museum from 2000\u20132005. (Robb is now curator of the [[Billy Ireland Cartoon Library & Museum]] in Columbus, Ohio.) Current curator [[Andrew Farago]] took over from Robb in 2005.\n\nIn 2001, the museum moved to a ground-floor location at 655 Mission Street in SoMa, which had been vacated by the [[Ansel Adams|Friends of Photography Ansel Adams Center]]{{Cn|date = April 2015}}. It closed the location in mid-September 2015 after the lease expired; the owners more than doubled the rent.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn late 2016, the museum signed a 10-year lease on a historic, 8,000-square-foot brick building a block away from [[Ghirardelli Square|Ghiradelli Square]]. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/11/03/cartoon-art-museum-finds-new-home-in-san-francisco/|title=Cartoon Art Museum Finds New Home in San Francisco|work=KQED Arts|access-date=2017-11-08|language=en-us}}</ref> Almost a year later, during late October 2017, the Cartoon Art Museum finally reopened its doors at its new location with three new exhibitions, including a retrospective of the San Francisco cartoonist [[Raina Telgemeier]], a tribute exhibition of [[Mike Mignola]]'s [[Hellboy]], and the emerging artist showcase featuring [[Nidhi Chanani]].\n\n== Sparky Award ==\nOver the years, the Museum has presented the '''Sparky Award''' (after the nickname of [[Charles M. Schulz]]), in honor of the lifetime achievement of prominent creators in the fields of cartooning and animation who \"embody the talent, innovation and humanity of Schulz.\"<ref name=Colan /> The award, which is co-sponsored by the [[Charles M. Schulz Museum]], includes a statuette of [[Snoopy]] holding a pen and leaning on an [[inkwell]]. (The CAM Sparky Award is not connected to the award of the same name presented at the [[Slamdance Film Festival]].)\n\nThe award debuted in 1998,<ref name=Flessel /> and multiple winners were announced each year until 2001. After a six-year hiatus, the award was again presented in 2007. The most recent Sparky Award was given in 2015.<ref name=Turner />\n\nThe Sparky Award has been presented at various venues, including the [[San Diego Comic-Con]] and the [[New York Comic Con]].\n\n'''List of Sparky Award winners''':<ref>[http://cartoonart.org/events/sparky-awards 2001 Sparky Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112005358/http://cartoonart.org/events/sparky-awards/ |date=2014-01-12 }}, www.cartoonart.org. Accessed Jan. 28, 2014.</ref>\n* 1998&nbsp;\u2013 [[Charles M. Schulz]], [[Chuck Jones]], and [[John Lasseter]]\n* 1999&nbsp;\u2013 [[Sergio Aragon\u00e9s]], [[Gus Arriola]], [[Carl Barks]], and [[Dale Messick]]\n* 2000&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ward Kimball]], [[Stan Lee]], and [[Morrie Turner]]\n* 2001&nbsp;\u2013 [[John Severin]], [[Will Eisner]], [[Phil Frank]], [[Lou Grant (cartoonist)|Lou Grant]], [[Gary Larson]], and [[Bill Mel\u00e9ndez]]\n* 2007&nbsp;\u2013 [[Creig Flessel]]<ref name=Flessel>Klien, Gary.\n[http://www.marinij.com/ci_7309002 \"Marin cartoonist, 95, wins 'Sparky' award,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222024248/http://www.marinij.com/ci_7309002 |date=2014-02-22 }} ''Marin Independent Journal'' (Oct. 28, 2007).</ref>\n* 2008&nbsp;\u2013 [[Gene Colan]]<ref name=Colan>[http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=19141 \"Gene Colan Awarded Sparky Award,\"] ''Comic Book Resources'' (December 11th, 2008).</ref> (and, in an earlier ceremony, [[Malcolm Whyte]])<ref>Garchik, Leah. [http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Friends-recall-William-Buckley-s-grace-3226277.php \"Friends recall William Buckley's grace,\"] ''San Francisco Chronicle'' (February 29, 2008): \"The Cartoon Art Museum in San Francisco threw a surprise 75th birthday party last week for its founder, Malcolm Whyte. The museum, which Whyte founded 25 years ago, is the world's largest devoted to cartoon art. Jeannie Schulz presented a Cartoon Art Museum \"Sparky\" award, named after her late husband, Charles Schulz, to Whyte, who was also given a caricature of himself by artist Zach Trenholm.\"</ref>\n* 2010&nbsp;\u2013 [[Mort Walker]]\n* 2011&nbsp;\u2013 [[Jerry Robinson]]\n* 2015&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ron Turner (publisher)|Ron Turner]]\u2014presented in conjunction with the first annual [[San Francisco Comics Fest]]<ref name=Turner>[http://icv2.com/articles/news/view/31529/san-francisco-proclaims-may-5-ron-turner-day \"SAN FRANCISCO PROCLAIMS MAY 5 'RON TURNER DAY': Legendary Publisher Also Gets 'Sparky Award',\"] ''ICv2'' (May 7, 2015).\n* 2017&nbsp;\u2013 [[Jeff Smith (cartoonist)|Jeff Smith]] presented at the Charles M. Schulz Museum and Research Center</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\nThe Museum hosts nine to 12 major exhibitions annually, along with classes for children and adults. It also offers lectures and operates a research library, a classroom and a bookstore.\n\n{{Portal|San Francisco Bay Area}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://cartoonart.org/}}\n* [https://twitter.com/cartoonart/ Twitter page]\n\n{{Comics}}\n{{Bay Area Arts Organizations}}\n{{San Francisco Attractions}}\n\n{{Coord|37.787088|-122.400940|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Art museums in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Cartooning museums]]\n[[Category:Media museums in California]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1984]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:South of Market, San Francisco]]\n[[Category:1984 in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Charles M. Schulz]]\n", "name_user": "Rontrigger", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartoon_Art_Museum"}
{"title_page": "Simon Coveney", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish Fine Gael politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Simon Coveney\n| honorific-suffix = [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]\n| image         = Simon Coveney 2018.jpg\n| office        = [[T\u00e1naiste]]\n| taoiseach     = [[Leo Varadkar]]\n| term_start    = 30 November 2017\n| term_end      = \n| predecessor   = [[Frances Fitzgerald (politician)|Frances Fitzgerald]]\n| successor     =\n| office1       = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade]]\n| taoiseach1    = Leo Varadkar\n| term_start1   = 14 June 2017\n| term_end1     = \n| predecessor1  = [[Charles Flanagan]]\n| successor1    =\n| office2       = [[Leader of Fine Gael#Deputy leaders|Deputy Leader of Fine Gael]]\n| leader2       = Leo Varadkar\n| term_start2   = 13 June 2017\n| term_end2     = \n| predecessor2  = [[James Reilly (Irish politician)|James Reilly]]\n| successor2    =\n| office3       = [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government]]\n| taoiseach3    = [[Enda Kenny]]\n| term_start3   = 6 May 2016\n| term_end3     = 14 June 2017\n| predecessor3  = [[Alan Kelly (politician)|Alan Kelly]]\n| successor3    = [[Eoghan Murphy]]\n| office4       = [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]]\n| taoiseach4    = Enda Kenny\n| term_start4   = 11 July 2014\n| term_end4     = 6 May 2016\n| predecessor4  = Enda Kenny {{small|(Acting)}}\n| successor4    = Enda Kenny\n| office5       = [[Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine]]\n| taoiseach5    = Enda Kenny\n| term_start5   = 9 March 2011\n| term_end5     = 6 May 2016\n| predecessor5  = [[Brendan Smith (politician)|Brendan Smith]]\n| successor5    = [[Michael Creed]]\n| office6       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start6   = [[1998 Cork South-Central by-election|October 1998]]\n| term_end6     = \n| constituency6 = [[Cork South-Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cork South-Central]]\n| office7       = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start7   = 20 July 2004\n| term_end7     = 24 June 2007\n| constituency7 = [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1972|6|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Ireland\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party         = [[Fine Gael]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Ruth Furney|2008}}\n| children      = 3\n| parents       = {{Ubl|[[Hugh Coveney]]|Pauline Coveney}}\n| education     = [[Clongowes Wood College]]\n| alma_mater    = {{Ubl|[[University College Cork]]|[[Gurteen College]]|[[Royal Agricultural University]]}}\n| website       = {{url|simoncoveney.ie}}\n|}}\n'''Simon Coveney''' (born 16 June 1972) is an Irish [[Fine Gael]] politician who has served as [[T\u00e1naiste]] since November 2017, [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade]] and [[Leader of Fine Gael#Deputy leaders|Deputy Leader of Fine Gael]] since June 2017. He has been a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Cork South-Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cork South-Central]] constituency since 1998. He previously served as [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government]] from 2016 to 2017, [[Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine]] from 2011 to 2016 and [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]] from 2014 to 2016. He served as a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for the [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]] constituency from 2004 to 2007.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Simon-Coveney.D.1998-10-23/|title=Simon Coveney|work=Oireachtas Members Database|accessdate=7 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nCoveney was born in [[Cork (city)|Cork]] and completed a BSc. in Agriculture from the [[Royal Agricultural College]], having earlier studied at [[University College Cork]]. He spent several years working as an agriculture adviser and farm manager. He was elected to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] in a by-election, following the death of his father [[Hugh Coveney]]. After an initial period on the backbenches, Coveney was promoted to the [[Fine Gael Front Bench|Front Bench]] by [[Michael Noonan (Fine Gael politician)|Michael Noonan]], as deputy chief whip, remaining in this position until a 2002 reshuffle, when he became [[Minister for Communications, Climate Action and Environment|Spokesperson on Communications, Marine and Natural Resources]] under [[Enda Kenny]]. A three-year period in the [[European Parliament]] was followed by a return to domestic politics in 2007, when he was appointed [[Minister for Communications, Climate Action and Environment|Spokesperson on Communications, Energy and Natural Resources]]. A 2010 reshuffle of the Front Bench saw him take over as [[Minister for Transport, Tourism and Sport|Spokesperson on Transport]].\n\nAfter the formation of the [[Government of the 31st D\u00e1il|coalition government]] in March 2011, Coveney was appointed [[Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine]]. Following a cabinet reshuffle in July 2014, which saw him also take over the position of [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]].<ref name=\"RT\u00c9\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0711/629951-cabinet/|title=Taoiseach announces new Cabinet|work=RT\u00c9 News|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> Following the formation of a [[Government of the 32nd D\u00e1il|Fine Gael minority government]] in May 2016, he was appointed [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Frances Fitzgerald is T\u00e1naiste in new Cabinet|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2016/0506/786692-cabinet-announcements/|publisher=RT\u00c9 News|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> In June 2017, after [[Leo Varadkar]] succeeded [[Enda Kenny]] as [[Taoiseach]], Varadkar appointed Coveney as Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade and Deputy Leader of Fine Gael. He was appointed [[T\u00e1naiste]] (Deputy Prime Minister) in November 2017, following the resignation of Frances Fitzgerald.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Coveney was the son of [[Hugh Coveney]] and Pauline Coveney. His father was a chartered [[quantity surveyor]] and later a [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]], and also a member of one of the famous merchant families in the city. He was educated locally in Cork, before later attending [[Clongowes Wood College]], [[County Kildare]]. He was expelled from the college in [[Transition Year]] but ultimately was invited back to complete his full six years there. He repeated his leaving certificate in Bruce college in Cork city,.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/radio1/miriammeets/280210.html|title=Miriam Meets...... Patrick and Simon Coveney, TD|work=[[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]]|accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref> Coveney subsequently attended [[University College Cork]] and [[Gurteen Agricultural College]], before completing a BSc in Agriculture and Land Management from [[Royal Agricultural University|Royal Agricultural College]], [[Gloucestershire]]. In 1997/8, he led the \u201cSail Chernobyl Project\u201d which involved sailing a boat 30,000 miles around the world and raising \u20ac650,000 for charity.\n\nHis brother, Patrick, is chief executive of the food corporation [[Greencore]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/fionnan-sheahan-its-game-on-in-fine-gael-as-simon-goes-on-a-listening-tour-and-leo-sees-his-lead-narrow-in-contest-35686031.html|title=Fionnan Sheahan: It's game on in Fine Gael as Simon goes on a listening tour and Leo sees his lead narrow in contest|work=Irish Independent|date=6 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Early years in D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann: 1998\u20132004===\nCoveney was elected to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] as a Fine Gael candidate for [[Cork South-Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cork South-Central]] in a [[1998 Cork South-Central by-election|by-election]], caused by the death of his father in 1998. In spite of being a strong supporter of party leader [[John Bruton]], he remained on the backbenches for a number of years.\n\nIn 2001, discipline in the parliamentary party broke down and Coveney came out against Bruton in a leadership heave. His loss of support was a surprise and encouraged others to vote against Bruton. The subsequent [[2001 Fine Gael leadership election|leadership contest]] was won by [[Michael Noonan (Fine Gael politician)|Michael Noonan]] and a new front bench was put in place. Coveney was subsequently promoted to the position of deputy chief whip.\n\nCoveney was re-elected at the [[2002 Irish general election|2002 general election]], in what turned out to be a disaster for Fine Gael. The party lost twenty-three seats and some of its most important party figures. Noonan was replaced as party leader by [[Enda Kenny]], who promoted Coveney to the position of Spokesperson on Communications, Marine and Natural Resources, in his new front bench.\n\n===Member of the European Parliament: 2004\u20132007===\nCoveney was elected to the [[European Parliament]] for the [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South constituency]], in the [[2004 European Parliament election in Ireland|2004 European Parliament election]]. During his three years as a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP), Coveney held the position of human rights co-ordinator for the largest political group in the European Parliament, the [[European People's Party]], and twice authored the Parliament's Annual Report on Human Rights in the world. He spearheaded the Stop the Traffic campaign at the European Parliament. He was a member of the Foreign Affairs Committee and the Delegation for Relations with the United States and a substitute on the Human Rights Subcommittee, Fisheries Committee, Internal Market and Consumer Protection Committee and the Delegation for Relations with Iran.\n\n===Return to the D\u00e1il: 2007\u20132011===\nCoveney returned to Ireland to contest the [[2007 Irish general election|2007 general election]]. He was successful in being returned to the D\u00e1il, as a result, he stepped down as a Member of the European Parliament. He was replaced in the European Parliament by [[Colm Burke]].<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?id=4443|title=Simon Coveney|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=7 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nFine Gael won back many of the seats that the party had lost five years earlier; however, they still fell short of forming a coalition government with the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]. Coveney returned to the party's front bench as Spokesperson on Communications, Energy and Natural Resources.\n\nIn June 2010, Coveney and a number of other front bench Spokespersons stated that they had [[Enda Kenny#Challenge to leadership: 2010|no confidence in their party leader]], Enda Kenny. A subsequent confidence motion in the leader was won by Kenny.<ref name=RTE_17062010>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/0617/finegael.html |title=Kenny survives confidence vote |work=[[RT\u00c9 News]] |date=17 June 2010 |accessdate=3 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619022616/http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/0617/finegael.html |archivedate=19 June 2010 }}</ref> Coveney was re-appointed to the front bench as Spokesperson on Transport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/0701/finegael.html |title=Bruton & Noonan return to Fine Gael frontbench |date=1 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 News]] |accessdate=3 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704030628/http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/0701/finegael.html |archivedate= 4 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine: 2011\u20132016===\nOn 9 March 2011, Coveney was appointed [[Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine]], in the new Fine Gael-Labour Party coalition government.\n\nHe attended his first [[Council of the European Union|meeting of EU Agriculture Ministers]], in [[Brussels]] on 17 March 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0316/agriculture.html|title=Simon Coveney to attend EU agriculture talks|work=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=16 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nCoveney provoked controversy when, in September 2011, he flew to [[Algeria]], on the government jet at a cost of more than \u20ac26,000 to the Irish taxpayer when there were flights available for \u20ac16,331.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/coveney-stands-by-euro26000-spend-on-government-jet-2929333.html|title=Coveney stands by \u20ac26,000 spend on government jet|last=McQuinn|first=Cormac|author2=Sheehan, Aideen |work=Irish Independent|date=9 November 2011|accessdate=9 November 2011}}</ref> While there, Coveney cut a ribbon at the opening of a supermarket in [[Oran]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/coveney-cut-ribbon-for-shop-on-euro26000-jet-trip-to-algeria-2927993.html|title=Coveney 'cut ribbon' for shop on \u20ac26,000 jet trip to Algeria|last=McQuinn|first=Cormac|work=Irish Independent|date=8 November 2011|accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.joe.ie/news-politics/current-affairs/the-government-minister-the-supermarket-opening-and-the-e26000-bill-0017517-1|title=The Government Minister, the supermarket-opening and the \u20ac26,000 bill|work=JOE|date=8 November 2011|accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Coveney attended a meeting of the [[Bilderberg Group]], in [[Copenhagen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/simon-coveney-bilderberg-conference-1490010-May2014/|title=This minister is heading to the secretive Bilderberg summit \u2013 but in a 'private capacity'|newspaper=[[TheJournal.ie]]|date=28 May  2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150608203319/http://www.thejournal.ie/simon-coveney-bilderberg-conference-1490010-May2014/|archivedate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for Defence: 2014\u20132016===\n[[File:Chief of Staff Lt Gen Conor O'Boyle briefs the Minister for Defence during a UN heli flight to 47 Infantry Group HQ.jpg|thumbnail|Fmr. [[Chief of Staff of the Defence Forces (Ireland)|Defence Forces Chief of Staff]] [[Lieutenant general|Lt Gen]] [[Conor O'Boyle]] briefing then Minister of Defence Simon Coveney]]\nOn 11 July 2014, Coveney was also appointed as [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]], in a cabinet reshuffle, following the resignation of [[Eamon Gilmore]] as [[T\u00e1naiste]]. He took over from [[Taoiseach]] [[Enda Kenny]], who was the acting Minister for Defence, following [[Alan Shatter]]'s resignation from cabinet, in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://static.rasset.ie/documents/news/alan-shatters-letter-of-resignation.pdf|format=PDF|title=Letter of resignation|website=Static.rasset.ie|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> As Minister for Defence, Coveney launched the [http://www.defence.ie/WebSite.nsf/WP2015E White Paper on Defence] in August 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Minihan|first1=Mary|title=Simon Coveney says Ireland has under-invested in defence|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/simon-coveney-says-ireland-has-under-invested-in-defence-1.2329828|accessdate=24 February 2017|newspaper=The Irish Times|date=27 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June 2015, Coveney questioned the judgment of an experienced Air Corps pilot who refused to fly him to Cork, because of predicted fog. In email correspondence between [[Department of Defence (Ireland)|Department of Defence]] officials, the Air Corps is described as being \u201cvery unhappy\u201d about the incident and<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/coveney-challenged-pilot-who-refused-to-fly-due-to-fog-forecast-1.3143597|title=Coveney challenged pilot who refused to fly due to fog forecast|website=Irishtimes.ie|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> indicating that they had never received such a call in 25 years.\u201d\n\n===Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government: 2016\u201317===\nOn 6 May 2016, Coveney was appointed the new [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government]], with Taoiseach Enda Kenny taking over the Defence portfolio and Fine Gael TD [[Michael Creed]] becoming the new Minister for Agriculture.<ref>{{cite news|title=Frances Fitzgerald is T\u00e1naiste in new Cabinet|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2016/0506/786692-cabinet-announcements/|accessdate=6 May 2016|publisher=RT\u00c9 News|date=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Fine Gael leadership election: 2017===\nOn 2 June 2017, Coveney lost the [[2017 Fine Gael leadership election]] to [[Leo Varadkar]], despite gaining the support of 65% of party members (party members only had 25% of the vote in Fine Gael's electoral college). The winner was expected to succeed [[Enda Kenny]] as [[Taoiseach]]. On 13 June 2017, it was announced that he would be the deputy leader of the party.<ref>{{cite news|title=Varadkar appoints Coveney as deputy Fine Gael leader|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2017/0613/882504-leo-varadkar-fine-gael/|publisher=RT\u00c9 News|date=13 June 2017|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade: 2017\u2013present===\n[[File:Secretary Tillerson and Irish Deputy Prime Minister Coveney Address Reporters in Washington (39549850925).jpg|thumb|Coveney with [[US Secretary of State]] [[Rex Tillerson]] in 2018]]\nAfter Leo Varadkar was appointed Taoiseach, by the [[President of Ireland]], as part of his new cabinet, Coveney was appointed [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade]], with special responsibilities for [[Brexit]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coveney appointed Irish foreign minister |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-40138423 |work=BBC News |date=15 June 2017}}</ref> Coveney replaced [[Charles Flanagan]], who became [[Minister for Justice and Equality]]. It was understood Coveney heavily lobbied Varadkar for the role as he wanted a large role on [[Brexit]]. In his capacity as Minister, he has also been co-chairing the [[European People's Party]] (EPP) [[European People's Party|Justice and Home Affairs Ministers Meeting]] since 2018, alongside [[Esteban Gonz\u00e1lez Pons]].<ref>[http://www.epp.eu/about-us/structure/ Council of the EU and Ministerial meetings] [[European People\u2019s Party]] (EPP).</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Lawrence Franklin]] of the [[Gatestone Institute]], within the Irish government, Coveney opposes the [[Control of Economic Activity (Occupied Territories) Bill]] to ban goods produced in [[Israeli settlements]]. He has expressed concern that the bill might contravene EU trade law.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Franklin |first1=Lawrence |title=Dublin's Anti-Israel Boycott Bill: Bad for Ireland, Worse for the Palestinians, Terrible for Everyone |url=https://spme.org/boycotts-divestments-sanctions-bds/boycotts-divestments-and-sanctions-bds-news/dublins-anti-israel-boycott-bill-bad-for-ireland-worse-for-the-palestinians-terrible-for-everyone/25598/ |publisher=Scholars for Peace in the Middle East |accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=29 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===T\u00e1naiste===\nOn 30 November 2017, Leo Varadkar named Coveney as the new [[T\u00e1naiste]], replacing [[Frances Fitzgerald (politician)|Frances Fitzgerald]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-new-tnaiste-simon-coveney-36367486.html |title=Everything you need to know about the new T\u00e1naiste Simon Coveney|date=1 December 2017|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Brexit negotiations====\nOn 27 January 2019, Coveney in an interview with [[Andrew Marr]], said the [[Irish backstop]] in the [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] will not be changed. He said the backstop was already a pragmatic compromise between the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[European Union]] to avoid infrastructure on the Irish border, that there was no sensible legally-sound alternative to the backstop, and that the European Parliament would not ratify a Brexit withdrawal agreement without the backstop in it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/there-will-be-no-change-to-the-brexit-backstop-says-coveney-1.3772249 |title=There will be no change to the Brexit backstop, says Coveney |work=Irish Times |date=2019-01-27}}</ref>\n\n====Coronavirus====\nAs acting Minister for Foreign Affairs, Conveney headed up the response to the Coronavirus Epidemic on behalf of the [[Government of Ireland]]. On 10 March 2020, he upgraded travel advice recommending that Irish Citizens do not travel to [[Italy]]. He added that people should think carefully about unnecessary public gatherings and urged the public to play their part and help themselves by following advice and doing practical things like sneezing and washing hands properly.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2020-03-10|title=Irish citizens recommended not to go to Italy - Coveney|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2020/0310/1121280-coveney-covid-19/|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCoveney married his long-time girlfriend Ruth Furney, an [[IDA Ireland]] employee, in July 2008. They have three daughters and live in [[Carrigaline]] in Cork.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/elections/latest-news/coveney-thinking-of-cots-not-cabinets-after-daughters-birth-2563675.html|title=Coveney thinking of cots, not cabinets, after daughter's birth|date=3 March 2011|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=11 March 2011|first=Ralph|last=Riegel}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Families in the Oireachtas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website|simoncoveney.ie}}\n*[https://www.finegael.ie/our-people/ministers/ministers/cork-south-central/simon-coveney/ Simon Coveney's page on the Fine Gael website]\n*[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sidesSearch/search.do?type=REPORT&language=EN&term=6&author=28118 Coveney authored reports on Human Rights in the World]\n*{{MEP|28118|Simon Coveney}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Hugh Coveney]]<br>{{small|[[Fine Gael]]}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Fine Gael]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]<br>for [[Cork South-Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cork South-Central]]\n       |years  = 1998\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of the European Parliament]]<br>for [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]]\n       |years  = 2004\u201307}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Colm Burke]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Brendan Smith (politician)|Brendan Smith]]|as=Minister for Agriculture, Fisheries and Food}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine]]\n       |years  = 2011\u201316}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Michael Creed]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Enda Kenny]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]]\n       |years  = 2014\u201316}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Enda Kenny]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Alan Kelly (politician)|Alan Kelly]]|as=Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government]]\n       |years  = 2016\u201317}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Eoghan Murphy]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Charles Flanagan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade]]\n       |years  = 2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Frances Fitzgerald (politician)|Frances Fitzgerald]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[T\u00e1naiste]]\n       |years  = 2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[James Reilly (Irish politician)|James Reilly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Leader of Fine Gael#Deputy leaders|Deputy Leader of Fine Gael]]\n       |years  = 2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Current Government of Ireland}}\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{Deputy heads of government of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Foreign Affairs of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Agriculture of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Defence of Ireland}}\n{{29th Government of Ireland}}\n{{30th Government of Ireland}}\n{{31st Government of Ireland}}\n{{Members of the European Parliament for Ireland (2004\u20132009)}}\n{{Fine Gael}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coveney, Simon}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Agricultural University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Cork]]\n[[Category:Fine Gael MEPs]]\n[[Category:Fine Gael TDs]]\n[[Category:Irish farmers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the 28th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 29th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 30th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 31st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 32nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 33rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the Republic of Ireland 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Agriculture (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Defence (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Clongowes Wood College]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Cork]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Foreign Affairs (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:T\u00e1naist\u00ed]]\n[[Category:People educated at Presentation Brothers College, Cork]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish Fine Gael politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Simon Coveney\n| honorific-suffix = [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]\n| image         = Simon Coveney 2018.jpg\n| office        = [[T\u00e1naiste]]\n| taoiseach     = [[Leo Varadkar]]\n| term_start    = 30 November 2017\n| term_end      = \n| predecessor   = [[Frances Fitzgerald (politician)|Frances Fitzgerald]]\n| successor     =\n| office1       = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade]]\n| taoiseach1    = Leo Varadkar\n| term_start1   = 14 June 2017\n| term_end1     = \n| predecessor1  = [[Charles Flanagan]]\n| successor1    =\n| office2       = [[Leader of Fine Gael#Deputy leaders|Deputy Leader of Fine Gael]]\n| leader2       = Leo Varadkar\n| term_start2   = 13 June 2017\n| term_end2     = \n| predecessor2  = [[James Reilly (Irish politician)|James Reilly]]\n| successor2    =\n| office3       = [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government]]\n| taoiseach3    = [[Enda Kenny]]\n| term_start3   = 6 May 2016\n| term_end3     = 14 June 2017\n| predecessor3  = [[Alan Kelly (politician)|Alan Kelly]]\n| successor3    = [[Eoghan Murphy]]\n| office4       = [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]]\n| taoiseach4    = Enda Kenny\n| term_start4   = 11 July 2014\n| term_end4     = 6 May 2016\n| predecessor4  = Enda Kenny {{small|(Acting)}}\n| successor4    = Enda Kenny\n| office5       = [[Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine]]\n| taoiseach5    = Enda Kenny\n| term_start5   = 9 March 2011\n| term_end5     = 6 May 2016\n| predecessor5  = [[Brendan Smith (politician)|Brendan Smith]]\n| successor5    = [[Michael Creed]]\n| office6       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start6   = [[1998 Cork South-Central by-election|October 1998]]\n| term_end6     = \n| constituency6 = [[Cork South-Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cork South-Central]]\n| office7       = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start7   = 20 July 2004\n| term_end7     = 24 June 2007\n| constituency7 = [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1972|6|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Ireland\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party         = [[Fine Gael]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Ruth Furney|2008}}\n| children      = 3\n| parents       = {{Ubl|[[Hugh Coveney]]|Pauline Coveney}}\n| education     = [[Clongowes Wood College]]\n| alma_mater    = {{Ubl|[[University College Cork]]|[[Gurteen College]]|[[Royal Agricultural University]]}}\n| website       = {{url|simoncoveney.ie}}\n|}}\n'''Simon Coveney''' (born 16 June 1972) is an Irish [[Fine Gael]] politician who has served as [[T\u00e1naiste]] since November 2017, [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade]] and [[Leader of Fine Gael#Deputy leaders|Deputy Leader of Fine Gael]] since June 2017. He has been a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Cork South-Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cork South-Central]] constituency since 1998. He previously served as [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government]] from 2016 to 2017, [[Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine]] from 2011 to 2016 and [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]] from 2014 to 2016. He served as a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for the [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]] constituency from 2004 to 2007.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Simon-Coveney.D.1998-10-23/|title=Simon Coveney|work=Oireachtas Members Database|accessdate=7 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nCoveney was born in [[Cork (city)|Cork]] and completed a BSc. in Agriculture from the [[Royal Agricultural College]], having earlier studied at [[University College Cork]]. He spent several years working as an agriculture adviser and farm manager. He was elected to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] in a by-election, following the death of his father [[Hugh Coveney]]. After an initial period on the backbenches, Coveney was promoted to the [[Fine Gael Front Bench|Front Bench]] by [[Michael Noonan (Fine Gael politician)|Michael Noonan]], as deputy chief whip, remaining in this position until a 2002 reshuffle, when he became [[Minister for Communications, Climate Action and Environment|Spokesperson on Communications, Marine and Natural Resources]] under [[Enda Kenny]]. A three-year period in the [[European Parliament]] was followed by a return to domestic politics in 2007, when he was appointed [[Minister for Communications, Climate Action and Environment|Spokesperson on Communications, Energy and Natural Resources]]. A 2010 reshuffle of the Front Bench saw him take over as [[Minister for Transport, Tourism and Sport|Spokesperson on Transport]].\n\nAfter the formation of the [[Government of the 31st D\u00e1il|coalition government]] in March 2011, Coveney was appointed [[Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine]]. Following a cabinet reshuffle in July 2014, which saw him also take over the position of [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]].<ref name=\"RT\u00c9\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0711/629951-cabinet/|title=Taoiseach announces new Cabinet|work=RT\u00c9 News|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> Following the formation of a [[Government of the 32nd D\u00e1il|Fine Gael minority government]] in May 2016, he was appointed [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Frances Fitzgerald is T\u00e1naiste in new Cabinet|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2016/0506/786692-cabinet-announcements/|publisher=RT\u00c9 News|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> In June 2017, after [[Leo Varadkar]] succeeded [[Enda Kenny]] as [[Taoiseach]], Varadkar appointed Coveney as Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade and Deputy Leader of Fine Gael. He was appointed [[T\u00e1naiste]] (Deputy Prime Minister) in November 2017, following the resignation of Frances Fitzgerald.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Coveney was the son of [[Hugh Coveney]] and Pauline Coveney. His father was a chartered [[quantity surveyor]] and later a [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]], and also a member of one of the famous merchant families in the city. He was educated locally in Cork, before later attending [[Clongowes Wood College]], [[County Kildare]]. He was expelled from the college in [[Transition Year]] but ultimately was invited back to complete his full six years there. He repeated his leaving certificate in Bruce college in Cork city,.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/radio1/miriammeets/280210.html|title=Miriam Meets...... Patrick and Simon Coveney, TD|work=[[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]]|accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref> Coveney subsequently attended [[University College Cork]] and [[Gurteen Agricultural College]], before completing a BSc in Agriculture and Land Management from [[Royal Agricultural University|Royal Agricultural College]], [[Gloucestershire]]. In 1997/8, he led the \u201cSail Chernobyl Project\u201d which involved sailing a boat 30,000 miles around the world and raising \u20ac650,000 for charity.\n\nHis brother, Patrick, is chief executive of the food corporation [[Greencore]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/fionnan-sheahan-its-game-on-in-fine-gael-as-simon-goes-on-a-listening-tour-and-leo-sees-his-lead-narrow-in-contest-35686031.html|title=Fionnan Sheahan: It's game on in Fine Gael as Simon goes on a listening tour and Leo sees his lead narrow in contest|work=Irish Independent|date=6 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Early years in D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann: 1998\u20132004===\nCoveney was elected to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] as a Fine Gael candidate for [[Cork South-Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cork South-Central]] in a [[1998 Cork South-Central by-election|by-election]], caused by the death of his father in 1998. In spite of being a strong supporter of party leader [[John Bruton]], he remained on the backbenches for a number of years.\n\nIn 2001, discipline in the parliamentary party broke down and Coveney came out against Bruton in a leadership heave. His loss of support was a surprise and encouraged others to vote against Bruton. The subsequent [[2001 Fine Gael leadership election|leadership contest]] was won by [[Michael Noonan (Fine Gael politician)|Michael Noonan]] and a new front bench was put in place. Coveney was subsequently promoted to the position of deputy chief whip.\n\nCoveney was re-elected at the [[2002 Irish general election|2002 general election]], in what turned out to be a disaster for Fine Gael. The party lost twenty-three seats and some of its most important party figures. Noonan was replaced as party leader by [[Enda Kenny]], who promoted Coveney to the position of Spokesperson on Communications, Marine and Natural Resources, in his new front bench.\n\n===Member of the European Parliament: 2004\u20132007===\nCoveney was elected to the [[European Parliament]] for the [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South constituency]], in the [[2004 European Parliament election in Ireland|2004 European Parliament election]]. During his three years as a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP), Coveney held the position of human rights co-ordinator for the largest political group in the European Parliament, the [[European People's Party]], and twice authored the Parliament's Annual Report on Human Rights in the world. He spearheaded the Stop the Traffic campaign at the European Parliament. He was a member of the Foreign Affairs Committee and the Delegation for Relations with the United States and a substitute on the Human Rights Subcommittee, Fisheries Committee, Internal Market and Consumer Protection Committee and the Delegation for Relations with Iran.\n\n===Return to the D\u00e1il: 2007\u20132011===\nCoveney returned to Ireland to contest the [[2007 Irish general election|2007 general election]]. He was successful in being returned to the D\u00e1il, as a result, he stepped down as a Member of the European Parliament. He was replaced in the European Parliament by [[Colm Burke]].<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?id=4443|title=Simon Coveney|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=7 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nFine Gael won back many of the seats that the party had lost five years earlier; however, they still fell short of forming a coalition government with the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]. Coveney returned to the party's front bench as Spokesperson on Communications, Energy and Natural Resources.\n\nIn June 2010, Coveney and a number of other front bench Spokespersons stated that they had [[Enda Kenny#Challenge to leadership: 2010|no confidence in their party leader]], Enda Kenny. A subsequent confidence motion in the leader was won by Kenny.<ref name=RTE_17062010>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/0617/finegael.html |title=Kenny survives confidence vote |work=[[RT\u00c9 News]] |date=17 June 2010 |accessdate=3 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619022616/http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/0617/finegael.html |archivedate=19 June 2010 }}</ref> Coveney was re-appointed to the front bench as Spokesperson on Transport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/0701/finegael.html |title=Bruton & Noonan return to Fine Gael frontbench |date=1 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 News]] |accessdate=3 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704030628/http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/0701/finegael.html |archivedate= 4 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine: 2011\u20132016===\nOn 9 March 2011, Coveney was appointed [[Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine]], in the new Fine Gael-Labour Party coalition government.\n\nHe attended his first [[Council of the European Union|meeting of EU Agriculture Ministers]], in [[Brussels]] on 17 March 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0316/agriculture.html|title=Simon Coveney to attend EU agriculture talks|work=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=16 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nCoveney provoked controversy when, in September 2011, he flew to [[Algeria]], on the government jet at a cost of more than \u20ac26,000 to the Irish taxpayer when there were flights available for \u20ac16,331.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/coveney-stands-by-euro26000-spend-on-government-jet-2929333.html|title=Coveney stands by \u20ac26,000 spend on government jet|last=McQuinn|first=Cormac|author2=Sheehan, Aideen |work=Irish Independent|date=9 November 2011|accessdate=9 November 2011}}</ref> While there, Coveney cut a ribbon at the opening of a supermarket in [[Oran]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/coveney-cut-ribbon-for-shop-on-euro26000-jet-trip-to-algeria-2927993.html|title=Coveney 'cut ribbon' for shop on \u20ac26,000 jet trip to Algeria|last=McQuinn|first=Cormac|work=Irish Independent|date=8 November 2011|accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.joe.ie/news-politics/current-affairs/the-government-minister-the-supermarket-opening-and-the-e26000-bill-0017517-1|title=The Government Minister, the supermarket-opening and the \u20ac26,000 bill|work=JOE|date=8 November 2011|accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Coveney attended a meeting of the [[Bilderberg Group]], in [[Copenhagen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/simon-coveney-bilderberg-conference-1490010-May2014/|title=This minister is heading to the secretive Bilderberg summit \u2013 but in a 'private capacity'|newspaper=[[TheJournal.ie]]|date=28 May  2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150608203319/http://www.thejournal.ie/simon-coveney-bilderberg-conference-1490010-May2014/|archivedate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for Defence: 2014\u20132016===\n[[File:Chief of Staff Lt Gen Conor O'Boyle briefs the Minister for Defence during a UN heli flight to 47 Infantry Group HQ.jpg|thumbnail|Fmr. [[Chief of Staff of the Defence Forces (Ireland)|Defence Forces Chief of Staff]] [[Lieutenant general|Lt Gen]] [[Conor O'Boyle]] briefing then Minister of Defence Simon Coveney]]\nOn 11 July 2014, Coveney was also appointed as [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]], in a cabinet reshuffle, following the resignation of [[Eamon Gilmore]] as [[T\u00e1naiste]]. He took over from [[Taoiseach]] [[Enda Kenny]], who was the acting Minister for Defence, following [[Alan Shatter]]'s resignation from cabinet, in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://static.rasset.ie/documents/news/alan-shatters-letter-of-resignation.pdf|format=PDF|title=Letter of resignation|website=Static.rasset.ie|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> As Minister for Defence, Coveney launched the [http://www.defence.ie/WebSite.nsf/WP2015E White Paper on Defence] in August 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Minihan|first1=Mary|title=Simon Coveney says Ireland has under-invested in defence|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/simon-coveney-says-ireland-has-under-invested-in-defence-1.2329828|accessdate=24 February 2017|newspaper=The Irish Times|date=27 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June 2015, Coveney questioned the judgment of an experienced Air Corps pilot who refused to fly him to Cork, because of predicted fog. In email correspondence between [[Department of Defence (Ireland)|Department of Defence]] officials, the Air Corps is described as being \u201cvery unhappy\u201d about the incident and<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/coveney-challenged-pilot-who-refused-to-fly-due-to-fog-forecast-1.3143597|title=Coveney challenged pilot who refused to fly due to fog forecast|website=Irishtimes.ie|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> indicating that they had never received such a call in 25 years.\u201d\n\n===Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government: 2016\u201317===\nOn 6 May 2016, Coveney was appointed the new [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government]], with Taoiseach Enda Kenny taking over the Defence portfolio and Fine Gael TD [[Michael Creed]] becoming the new Minister for Agriculture.<ref>{{cite news|title=Frances Fitzgerald is T\u00e1naiste in new Cabinet|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2016/0506/786692-cabinet-announcements/|accessdate=6 May 2016|publisher=RT\u00c9 News|date=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Fine Gael leadership election: 2017===\nOn 2 June 2017, Coveney lost the [[2017 Fine Gael leadership election]] to [[Leo Varadkar]], despite gaining the support of 65% of party members (party members only had 25% of the vote in Fine Gael's electoral college). The winner was expected to succeed [[Enda Kenny]] as [[Taoiseach]]. On 13 June 2017, it was announced that he would be the deputy leader of the party.<ref>{{cite news|title=Varadkar appoints Coveney as deputy Fine Gael leader|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2017/0613/882504-leo-varadkar-fine-gael/|publisher=RT\u00c9 News|date=13 June 2017|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade: 2017\u2013present===\n[[File:Secretary Tillerson and Irish Deputy Prime Minister Coveney Address Reporters in Washington (39549850925).jpg|thumb|Coveney with [[US Secretary of State]] [[Rex Tillerson]] in 2018]]\nAfter Leo Varadkar was appointed Taoiseach, by the [[President of Ireland]], as part of his new cabinet, Coveney was appointed [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade]], with special responsibilities for [[Brexit]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coveney appointed Irish foreign minister |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-40138423 |work=BBC News |date=15 June 2017}}</ref> Coveney replaced [[Charles Flanagan]], who became [[Minister for Justice and Equality]]. It was understood Coveney heavily lobbied Varadkar for the role as he wanted a large role on [[Brexit]]. In his capacity as Minister, he has also been co-chairing the [[European People's Party]] (EPP) [[European People's Party|Justice and Home Affairs Ministers Meeting]] since 2018, alongside [[Esteban Gonz\u00e1lez Pons]].<ref>[http://www.epp.eu/about-us/structure/ Council of the EU and Ministerial meetings] [[European People\u2019s Party]] (EPP).</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Lawrence Franklin]] of the [[Gatestone Institute]], within the Irish government, Coveney opposes the [[Control of Economic Activity (Occupied Territories) Bill]] to ban goods produced in [[Israeli settlements]]. He has expressed concern that the bill might contravene EU trade law.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Franklin |first1=Lawrence |title=Dublin's Anti-Israel Boycott Bill: Bad for Ireland, Worse for the Palestinians, Terrible for Everyone |url=https://spme.org/boycotts-divestments-sanctions-bds/boycotts-divestments-and-sanctions-bds-news/dublins-anti-israel-boycott-bill-bad-for-ireland-worse-for-the-palestinians-terrible-for-everyone/25598/ |publisher=Scholars for Peace in the Middle East |accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=29 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===T\u00e1naiste===\nOn 30 November 2017, Leo Varadkar named Coveney as the new [[T\u00e1naiste]], replacing [[Frances Fitzgerald (politician)|Frances Fitzgerald]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-new-tnaiste-simon-coveney-36367486.html |title=Everything you need to know about the new T\u00e1naiste Simon Coveney|date=1 December 2017|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Brexit negotiations====\nOn 27 January 2019, Coveney in an interview with [[Andrew Marr]], said the [[Irish backstop]] in the [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] will not be changed. He said the backstop was already a pragmatic compromise between the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[European Union]] to avoid infrastructure on the Irish border, that there was no sensible legally-sound alternative to the backstop, and that the European Parliament would not ratify a Brexit withdrawal agreement without the backstop in it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/there-will-be-no-change-to-the-brexit-backstop-says-coveney-1.3772249 |title=There will be no change to the Brexit backstop, says Coveney |work=Irish Times |date=2019-01-27}}</ref>\n\n====Coronavirus====\nAs Minister for Foreign Affairs, Conveney headed up the response to the Coronavirus Epidemic on behalf of the [[Government of Ireland]]. On 10 March 2020, he upgraded travel advice recommending that Irish Citizens do not travel to [[Italy]]. He added that people should think carefully about unnecessary public gatherings and urged the public to play their part and help themselves by following advice and doing practical things like sneezing and washing hands properly.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2020-03-10|title=Irish citizens recommended not to go to Italy - Coveney|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2020/0310/1121280-coveney-covid-19/|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCoveney married his long-time girlfriend Ruth Furney, an [[IDA Ireland]] employee, in July 2008. They have three daughters and live in [[Carrigaline]] in Cork.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/elections/latest-news/coveney-thinking-of-cots-not-cabinets-after-daughters-birth-2563675.html|title=Coveney thinking of cots, not cabinets, after daughter's birth|date=3 March 2011|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=11 March 2011|first=Ralph|last=Riegel}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Families in the Oireachtas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website|simoncoveney.ie}}\n*[https://www.finegael.ie/our-people/ministers/ministers/cork-south-central/simon-coveney/ Simon Coveney's page on the Fine Gael website]\n*[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sidesSearch/search.do?type=REPORT&language=EN&term=6&author=28118 Coveney authored reports on Human Rights in the World]\n*{{MEP|28118|Simon Coveney}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Hugh Coveney]]<br>{{small|[[Fine Gael]]}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Fine Gael]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]<br>for [[Cork South-Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cork South-Central]]\n       |years  = 1998\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of the Europea