{"title_page": "Surani, Prahova", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Prahova\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Prahova County\n|name=Surani\n|image_map              = Surani jud Prahova.png\n|coordinates = {{coord|45|12|N|26|12|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Surani''' is a [[communes of Romania|commune]] in [[Prahova County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of two villages, P\u0103curi and Surani.\n\n{{Prahova County}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Prahova County|Surani]]\n\n\n{{Prahova-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Prahova\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Prahova County\n|name=Surani\n|image_map=\n|coordinates = {{coord|45|12|N|26|12|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Surani''' is a [[communes of Romania|commune]] in [[Prahova County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of two villages, P\u0103curi and Surani.\n\n{{Prahova County}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Prahova County|Surani]]\n\n\n{{Prahova-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surani,_Prahova"}
{"title_page": "Noisy friarbird", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of bird}}\n{{Speciesbox\n | name = Noisy friarbird\n | image = Philemon corniculatus - Glen Davis.jpg\n | status = LC\n | status_system = IUCN3.1\n | status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704227/0 |title=''Philemon corniculatus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n | genus = Philemon\n | species = corniculatus\n | authority = [[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1790\n | range_map = Noisy Friarbird.png\n | range_map_caption = Distribution of the noisy friarbird in Australia\n}}\n\nThe '''noisy friarbird''' (''Philemon corniculatus'') is a [[passerine]] bird of the honeyeater family [[Meliphagidae]] native to southern [[New Guinea]] and eastern [[Australia]]. It is one of several species known as [[friarbird]]s whose heads are bare of feathers. It is brown-grey in colour, with a prominent knob on its bare black-skinned head. It feeds on insects and nectar.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe noisy friarbird was first described by ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] in 1790. Its specific epithet is derived from the [[Latin]] ''corniculum'' '(having a) little horn'.<ref>{{cite book|author = Simpson DP| title = Cassell's Latin Dictionary  | publisher = Cassell Ltd.| year = 1979|edition = 5th|location = London| isbn=0-304-52257-0|page = 883}}</ref>  It is sometimes known as a ''Leatherhead''.<ref name=Wade77>{{cite book |editor=Wade, P. |year=1977 |title=Every Australian Bird Illustrated |publisher=Rigby |isbn=0-7270-0009-8 |page=265}}</ref> ''Wirgan'' was a name used by the local [[Eora]] and [[Darug people|Darug]] inhabitants of the Sydney basin.<ref>{{cite book |author=Troy, Jakelin |year=1993 |title=The Sydney Language |publisher=Jakelin Troy |location=Canberra |isbn=0-646-11015-2 |page=55}}</ref>\n\nMolecular study shows its closest relative to be the [[silver-crowned friarbird]] within the genus ''Philemon''.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.ympev.2003.10.017 | last1 = Driskell | first1 = A.C. | last2 = Christidis | first2 = L | year = 2004 | title = Phylogeny and evolution of the Australo-Papuan honeyeaters (Passeriformes, Meliphagidae) | url = | journal = Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume = 31 | issue = 3| pages = 943\u2013960 | pmid = 15120392 }}</ref> [[DNA]] analysis has shown honeyeaters to be related to the [[Pardalotidae]] (pardalotes), [[Acanthizidae]] (Australian warblers, scrubwrens, thornbills, etc.), and [[Maluridae]] (Australian fairy-wrens) in a large [[Meliphagoidea]] superfamily.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0401892101 | last1 = Barker | first1 = F.K. | last2 = Cibois | first2 = A. | last3 = Schikler | first3 = P. | last4 = Feinstein | first4 = J. | last5 = Cracraft | first5 = J | year = 2004 | title = Phylogeny and diversification of the largest avian radiation | url = | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America| volume = 101 | issue = 30| pages = 11040\u201311045 | pmid=15263073 | pmc=503738}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Noisy friarbird closeup.JPG|thumb|Head]]\nMeasuring {{convert|31|\u2013|36|cm|in|round=0.5|abbr=on}} in length, the noisy friarbird is a large honeyeater with dull brownish grey upperparts and paler brown-grey underparts. Its black head is completely bald apart from tufts of feathers under the chin and along the eyebrow, which is how it came to be so named. It can be distinguished by its rounded knob above the black bill, which is visible at distance. It has dark blue-black legs and red eyes.<ref name=Slater74>{{cite book |last=Slater |first=Peter |year=1974 |title=A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Non-passerines |location=Adelaide |publisher=Rigby |isbn=0-85179-813-6|page=245}}</ref>\n\nAs its name suggests, it is noisy; one of its calls has been likened to \"four o'clock\".<ref name=Wade77/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe natural range is from the vicinity of [[Lakes Entrance, Victoria|Lakes Entrance]] and the [[Murray River|Murray valley]] in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], north through [[New South Wales]] and [[Queensland]] to [[Cape York Peninsula|Cape York]].<ref name=Slater74/> In New Guinea it is restricted to the [[Trans-Fly savanna and grasslands|Trans-Fly]] in the south of the island where it is locally abundant.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Beehler, Bruce M. |author2=Pratt, Thane K. |author3=Zimmerman, Dale A. |year=1986|title=Birds of New Guinea|publisher=Princeton University Press| location=Princeton, New Jersey|isbn=0-691-08385-1|page=205}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour==\nIn southern parts of eastern Australia the species is migratory, moving north to overwinter and returning south in the spring. Large aggregations of noisy friarbirds are possible, often in association with [[little friarbird]]s. At such times, the constant cackling and chattering of the noisy friarbird can fill the forest with sound. The calls are used to identify an individual's feeding territory, and also announce the presence of food sources worth defending to other birds\u2014not necessarily friarbirds alone. Their diet consists of nectar, insects, and fruit. The consumption of commercially grown fruit, such as grapes and berries, can bring noisy friarbirds into direct conflict with humans who may regard them as pests under those circumstances. They are aggressively protective of their nests, and are known to swoop.\n\n===Breeding===\nBreeding may occur from July to January, with one or two broods during this time. The nest is a large, deep cup with an inverted lip or rim, made of bark and grass hanging from a horizontal branch, 1\u20133 metres above the ground, and usually well-hidden. Two to four (rarely five) eggs are laid, 22 \u00d7 33&nbsp;mm (1 \u00d7 {{frac|1|1|3}} in), and buff- to pale-pink splotched with darker pink-brown or purplish colours.<ref>{{cite book |last=Beruldsen |first=G |title=Australian Birds: Their Nests and Eggs |publisher=self |year=2003 |location=Kenmore Hills, Qld | isbn=0-646-42798-9 |page=317}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Philemon corniculatus 2 - Glen Davis.jpg|Adult in New South Wales\nFile:Philemon corniculatus -Canberra, Australia -juvenile-8 (1).jpg|Juvenile in Canberra, Australia\nFile:Noisy Friarbird.jpg|Adult by nest\nFile:Noisy-friar.JPG|Noisy Friarbird, Canungra, Queensland\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* ''[[Reader's Digest Complete Book of Australian Birds|Complete Book of Australian Birds]]''. Reader's Digest (Australia). 1997.\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q739101}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:friarbird, noisy}}\n[[Category:Birds described in 1790]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Papua New Guinea]]\n[[Category:Birds of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Philemon (bird)|noisy friarbird]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of bird}}\n{{Speciesbox\n | name = Noisy friarbird\n | image = Philemon corniculatus - Glen Davis.jpg\n | status = LC\n | status_system = IUCN3.1\n | status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704227/0 |title=''Philemon corniculatus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n | genus = Philemon\n | species = corniculatus\n | authority = [[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1790\n | range_map = Noisy Friarbird.png\n | range_map_caption = Distribution of the noisy friarbird in Australia\n}}\n\nThe '''noisy friarbird''' (''Philemon corniculatus'') is a [[passerine]] bird of the honeyeater family [[Meliphagidae]] native to southern [[New Guinea]] and eastern [[Australia]]. It is one of several species known as [[friarbird]]s whose heads are bare of feathers. It is brown-grey in colour, with a prominent knob on its bare black-skinned head. It feeds on insects and nectar.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe noisy friarbird was first described by ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] in 1790. Its specific epithet is derived from the [[Latin]] ''corniculum'' '(having a) little horn'.<ref>{{cite book|author = Simpson DP| title = Cassell's Latin Dictionary  | publisher = Cassell Ltd.| year = 1979|edition = 5th|location = London| isbn=0-304-52257-0|page = 883}}</ref>  It is sometimes known as a ''Leatherhead''.<ref name=Wade77>{{cite book |editor=Wade, P. |year=1977 |title=Every Australian Bird Illustrated |publisher=Rigby |isbn=0-7270-0009-8 |page=265}}</ref> ''Wirgan'' was a name used by the local [[Eora]] and [[Darug people|Darug]] inhabitants of the Sydney basin.<ref>{{cite book |author=Troy, Jakelin |year=1993 |title=The Sydney Language |publisher=Jakelin Troy |location=Canberra |isbn=0-646-11015-2 |page=55}}</ref>\n\nMolecular study shows its closest relative to be the [[silver-crowned friarbird]] within the genus ''Philemon''.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.ympev.2003.10.017 | last1 = Driskell | first1 = A.C. | last2 = Christidis | first2 = L | year = 2004 | title = Phylogeny and evolution of the Australo-Papuan honeyeaters (Passeriformes, Meliphagidae) | url = | journal = Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume = 31 | issue = 3| pages = 943\u2013960 | pmid = 15120392 }}</ref> [[DNA]] analysis has shown honeyeaters to be related to the [[Pardalotidae]] (pardalotes), [[Acanthizidae]] (Australian warblers, scrubwrens, thornbills, etc.), and [[Maluridae]] (Australian fairy-wrens) in a large [[Meliphagoidea]] superfamily.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0401892101 | last1 = Barker | first1 = F.K. | last2 = Cibois | first2 = A. | last3 = Schikler | first3 = P. | last4 = Feinstein | first4 = J. | last5 = Cracraft | first5 = J | year = 2004 | title = Phylogeny and diversification of the largest avian radiation | url = | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America| volume = 101 | issue = 30| pages = 11040\u201311045 | pmid=15263073 | pmc=503738}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Noisy friarbird closeup.JPG|thumb|Head]]\nMeasuring {{convert|31|\u2013|36|cm|in|round=0.5|abbr=on}} in length, the noisy friarbird is a large honeyeater with dull brownish grey upperparts and paler brown-grey underparts. Its black head is completely bald apart from tufts of feathers under the chin and along the eyebrow, which is how it came to be so named. It can be distinguished by its rounded knob above the black bill, which is visible at distance. It has dark blue-black legs and red eyes.<ref name=Slater74>{{cite book |last=Slater |first=Peter |year=1974 |title=A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Non-passerines |location=Adelaide |publisher=Rigby |isbn=0-85179-813-6|page=245}}</ref>\n\nAs its name suggests, it is noisy; one of its calls has been likened to \"four o'clock\".<ref name=Wade77/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe natural range is from the vicinity of [[Lakes Entrance, Victoria|Lakes Entrance]] and the [[Murray River|Murray valley]] in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], north through [[New South Wales]] and [[Queensland]] to [[Cape York Peninsula|Cape York]].<ref name=Slater74/> In New Guinea it is restricted to the [[Trans-Fly savanna and grasslands|Trans-Fly]] in the south of the island where it is locally abundant.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Beehler, Bruce M. |author2=Pratt, Thane K. |author3=Zimmerman, Dale A. |year=1986|title=Birds of New Guinea|publisher=Princeton University Press| location=Princeton, New Jersey|isbn=0-691-08385-1|page=205}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour==\nIn southern parts of eastern Australia the species is migratory, moving north to overwinter and returning south in the spring. Large aggregations of noisy friarbirds are possible, often in association with [[little friarbird]]s. At such times, the constant cackling and chattering of the noisy friarbird can fill the forest with sound. The calls are used to identify an individual's feeding territory, and also announce the presence of food sources worth defending to other birds\u2014not necessarily friarbirds alone. Their diet consists of nectar, insects, and fruit. The consumption of commercially grown fruit, such as grapes and berries, can bring noisy friarbirds into direct conflict with humans who may regard them as pests under those circumstances. They are aggressively protective of their nests, and are known to swoop.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Philemon corniculatus 2 - Glen Davis.jpg|Adult in New South Wales\nFile:Philemon corniculatus -Canberra, Australia -juvenile-8 (1).jpg|Juvenile in Canberra, Australia\nFile:Noisy Friarbird.jpg|Adult by nest\nFile:Noisy-friar.JPG|Noisy Friarbird, Canungra, Queensland\n</gallery>\n\n===Breeding===\nBreeding may occur from July to January, with one or two broods during this time. The nest is a large, deep cup with an inverted lip or rim, made of bark and grass hanging from a horizontal branch, 1\u20133 metres above the ground, and usually well-hidden. Two to four (rarely five) eggs are laid, 22 \u00d7 33&nbsp;mm (1 \u00d7 {{frac|1|1|3}} in), and buff- to pale-pink splotched with darker pink-brown or purplish colours.<ref>{{cite book |last=Beruldsen |first=G |title=Australian Birds: Their Nests and Eggs |publisher=self |year=2003 |location=Kenmore Hills, Qld | isbn=0-646-42798-9 |page=317}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* ''[[Reader's Digest Complete Book of Australian Birds|Complete Book of Australian Birds]]''. Reader's Digest (Australia). 1997.\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q739101}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:friarbird, noisy}}\n[[Category:Birds described in 1790]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Papua New Guinea]]\n[[Category:Birds of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Philemon (bird)|noisy friarbird]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBehaviour:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noisy_friarbird"}
{"title_page": "S\u00e9rgio Trindade", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = S\u00e9rgio Trindade\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 14 December 1940\n| birth_place   = [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2020|03|18|1940|12|14}}\n| death_place   = [[New York City]], [[United States]]\n| nationality   = [[Brazilian people|Brazilian]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Chemical engineer\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''S\u00e9rgio Trindade''' (14 December 1940 \u2013 18 March 2020) was a Brazilian chemical engineer and researcher.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eco21.eco.br/cientista-ambiental-sergio-trindade-morre-vitima-do-covid-19/|title=S\u00e9rgio Trindade morre v\u00edtima do COVID-19|work=ECO21|language=Portuguese}}</ref> He specialized in renewable energy and sustainable economic development, which helped him win the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] in 2007 for his role on the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/sociedade/coronavirus/brasileiro-que-integrou-equipe-vencedora-do-premio-nobel-da-paz-morre-por-coronavirus-1-24318156|title=Brasileiro que integrou equipe vencedora do Pr\u00eamio Nobel da Paz morre por coronav\u00edrus|date=20 March 2020|work=O Globo|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://polarconnection.org/profiles-advisory-bo/sergio-c-trindade/|title=Sergio C. Trindade|work=The Polar Connection, Home of Polar Research and Policy Initiative}}</ref> The Panel shared this award with [[Al Gore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/peace/2007/award-video/|title=The Nobel Peace Prize Award Ceremony 2007|date=2007|work=The Nobel Prize}}</ref>\n\nA graduate of the [[Federal University of Rio de Janeiro]], Trindade earned a doctorate at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.senado.leg.br/bdsf/bitstream/handle/id/413229/noticia.htm?sequence=1|title=Um brasileiro no Nobel da Paz 2007|date=18 November 2007|work=O Globo|language=Portuguese}}</ref> He died in [[New York City]] on 18 March 2020 of [[COVID-19]]. He was 79.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cryptodictation.com/2020/03/21/sergio-trindade-brazilian-nobel-winning-scientist-is-yet-another-victim-of-the-coronavirus/|title=S\u00e9rgio Trindade, Brazilian Nobel-winning scientist, is yet another victim of the coronavirus|date=21 March 2020|work=Cryptodictation}}</ref><ref>https://g1.globo.com/ciencia-e-saude/noticia/2020/03/20/sergio-trindade-cientista-brasileiro-do-ipcc-e-ganhador-do-nobel-da-paz-morre-aos-79-anos-vitima-de-covid-19-diz-agencia.ghtml</ref>\n==References==\n\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Brazilian chemical engineers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Federal University of Rio de Janeiro alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = S\u00e9rgio Trindade\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 14 December 1940\n| birth_place   = [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2020|03|18|1940|12|14}}\n| death_place   = [[New York City]], [[United States]]\n| nationality   = [[Brazilian people|Brazilian]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Chemical engineer\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''S\u00e9rgio Trindade''' (14 December 1940 \u2013 18 March 2020) was a Brazilian chemical engineer and researcher.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eco21.eco.br/cientista-ambiental-sergio-trindade-morre-vitima-do-covid-19/|title=S\u00e9rgio Trindade morre v\u00edtima do COVID-19|work=ECO21|language=Portuguese}}</ref> He specialized in renewable energy and sustainable economic development, which helped him win the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] in 2007 for his role on the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/sociedade/coronavirus/brasileiro-que-integrou-equipe-vencedora-do-premio-nobel-da-paz-morre-por-coronavirus-1-24318156|title=Brasileiro que integrou equipe vencedora do Pr\u00eamio Nobel da Paz morre por coronav\u00edrus|date=20 March 2020|work=O Globo|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://polarconnection.org/profiles-advisory-bo/sergio-c-trindade/|title=Sergio C. Trindade|work=The Polar Connection, Home of Polar Research and Policy Initiative}}</ref> The Panel shared this award with [[Al Gore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/peace/2007/award-video/|title=The Nobel Peace Prize Award Ceremony 2007|date=2007|work=The Nobel Prize}}</ref>\n\nA graduate of the [[Federal University of Rio de Janeiro]], Trindade earned a doctorate at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.senado.leg.br/bdsf/bitstream/handle/id/413229/noticia.htm?sequence=1|title=Um brasileiro no Nobel da Paz 2007|date=18 November 2007|work=O Globo|language=Portuguese}}</ref> He died in [[New York City]] on 18 March 2020 due to [[COVID-19]]. He was 79.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cryptodictation.com/2020/03/21/sergio-trindade-brazilian-nobel-winning-scientist-is-yet-another-victim-of-the-coronavirus/|title=S\u00e9rgio Trindade, Brazilian Nobel-winning scientist, is yet another victim of the coronavirus|date=21 March 2020|work=Cryptodictation}}</ref><ref>https://g1.globo.com/ciencia-e-saude/noticia/2020/03/20/sergio-trindade-cientista-brasileiro-do-ipcc-e-ganhador-do-nobel-da-paz-morre-aos-79-anos-vitima-de-covid-19-diz-agencia.ghtml</ref>\n==References==\n\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Brazilian chemical engineers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Federal University of Rio de Janeiro alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change members]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%C3%A9rgio_Trindade"}
